  "text": "Although further investigation needs to be conducted to determine why these changes happen at this transition point, the basic pattern can be explained in terms of the properties of the theoretical lexical similarity space in which these targets reside as it is collapsed across visually indistinguishable dimensions [CITATION_1] . Recall that expected class size is the number of words expected to be visually equivalent to a target after visemic transcription. Words that are visually equivalent form equivalence classes. Although Auer and Bernstein do not discuss the issue per se, words in dense neighborhoods are going to be more likely to collapse into equivalence classes with high class sizes, because there are simply more words with the potential to be visually equivalent. This is because neighbors differ from a target word in only one phoneme. With more neighbors comes the increased possibility that, after visual transcription, the last, differing phoneme will also be considered visually equivalent. This likelihood increases as the viseme criterion is relaxed. Thus, at the most lax criteria, simply picking a response from the neighborhood of the target word will usually be sufficient for a correct response.",
